04509nam a22005895i 9780822374572DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20162016ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223745727 a10.1515/97808223745722doi  a(DE-B1597)552310  a(OCoLC)1170224335  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aP119.32.P45bR34 2016 7aLAN0230002bisacsh04a306.4495992231 aRafael, Vicente L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMotherless Tongues :bThe Insurgency of Language amid Wars of Translation /cVicente L. Rafael. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2016  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b13 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. The Aporia of Translation -- tPART I. Vernacularizing the political -- tCHAPTER 1. Welcoming What Comes -- tCHAPTER 2. Wars of Translation -- tCHAPTER 3. The Cell Phone and the Crowd -- tPART II. Weaponizing babel -- tCHAPTER 4. Translation, American English, and the National Insecurities of Empire -- tCHAPTER 5. Targeting Translation -- tPART III. Translating Lives -- tCHAPTER 6. The Accidents of Area Studies -- tCHAPTER 7. Contracting Nostalgia -- tCHAPTER 8. Language, History, and Autobiography -- tCHAPTER 9. Interview -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Motherless Tongues, Vicente L. Rafael examines the vexed relationship between language and history gleaned from the workings of translation in the Philippines, the United States, and beyond. Moving across a range of colonial and postcolonial settings, he demonstrates translation's agency in the making and understanding of events. These include nationalist efforts to vernacularize politics, U.S. projects to weaponize languages in wartime, and autobiographical attempts by area studies scholars to translate the otherness of their lives amid the Cold War. In all cases, translation is at war with itself, generating divergent effects. It deploys as well as distorts American English in counterinsurgency and colonial education, for example, just as it re-articulates European notions of sovereignty among Filipino revolutionaries in the nineteenth century and spurs the circulation of text messages in a civilian-driven coup in the twenty-first. Along the way, Rafael delineates the untranslatable that inheres in every act of translation, asking about the politics and ethics of uneven linguistic and semiotic exchanges. Mapping those moments where translation and historical imagination give rise to one another, Motherless Tongues shows how translation, in unleashing the insurgency of language, simultaneously sustains and subverts regimes of knowledge and relations of power.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aColonial influence. 0aLanguage and languagesxPolitical aspects. 0aPhilippine languagesxPolitical aspects. 0aTranslating and interpretingxPolitical aspectsxPhilippines. 0aTranslating and interpretingxPolitical aspectszPhilippines. 0aTranslating and interpretingxPolitical aspects. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Translating & Interpreting.2bisacsh  aPhilippines National Book Award winner.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831107080800 cprintz978082236058240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822374572?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822374572423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822374572/original  a978-3-11-070808-0  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles